	<!-- CONTENT -->
	<section class="section section-cream">
		<div class="blog-post reveal">
			<div class="blog-post-meta">
				<p class="meta-info">Published April 1, 2026 · By the Sula Catering Team</p>
			</div>

			<p>Not every Indian dish belongs at an office lunch. Some are too messy. Some are too heavy. Some don't travel. Some put the entire team in food coma at 2 PM. After fifteen years of catering Vancouver corporate events, we've narrowed down the dishes that consistently win — the ones that satisfy without slowing the afternoon down.</p>

			<h2>The <em>Crowd-Pleasers</em></h2>

			<h3>Butter Chicken</h3>
			<p>It's a cliché for a reason. Mild enough for cautious eaters, rich enough to feel indulgent, universally familiar. Travels well, holds heat beautifully, and even sceptical first-time-Indian-food eaters will eat it. If you only order one chicken dish, this is it.</p>

			<h3>Chicken Tikka Masala</h3>
			<p>Slightly more flavourful than butter chicken, with a tangier sauce and grilled chicken pieces. Pairs beautifully with naan or basmati rice. Almost as universal as butter chicken, with a little more depth.</p>

			<h3>Paneer Butter Masala</h3>
			<p>The vegetarian counterpart to butter chicken — creamy, rich, comforting. Vegetarians always appreciate having a substantial main rather than just a vegetable side. This dish makes them feel like the menu was built for them too.</p>

			<h3>Dal Makhani</h3>
			<p>Slow-cooked black lentils in a buttery tomato base. Vegan-friendly with a substitution. Holds heat for hours, transports well, and works as either a main or a hearty side.</p>

			<h2>The <em>Reliable Sides</em></h2>

			<h3>Basmati Rice</h3>
			<p>Plain or pulao with peas and cumin. The neutral base that lets the curries shine. Don't overcomplicate this.</p>

			<h3>Garlic Naan</h3>
			<p>Crowd favourite. Order generously — naan disappears faster than you'd expect. Plain naan is a good option for guests with garlic sensitivities.</p>

			<h3>Mixed Vegetable Curry</h3>
			<p>A vegan-friendly side that gives non-meat-eaters a second option beyond paneer. Cauliflower, peas, carrots, beans in a light tomato-cumin base. Travels well and pleases dietary purists.</p>

			<h2>The <em>Smart Starters</em></h2>

			<h3>Samosas</h3>
			<p>Hands-down the easiest starter to serve at an office lunch. No utensils needed, holds heat well, vegetarian by default, and almost everyone has had one before. Serve with mint-coriander and tamarind chutneys.</p>

			<h3>Vegetable Pakoras</h3>
			<p>Crispy, savoury, gluten-friendly when made with pure chickpea flour. Great as a passed appetiser if your meeting has a stand-up reception component.</p>

			<h3>Tikka or Kebab Skewers</h3>
			<p>For more elevated corporate events — chicken tikka, paneer tikka, or seekh kebabs on small skewers. Easy to grab, photograph beautifully, and feel premium without being fussy.</p>

			<h2>What to <em>Avoid</em></h2>

			<p>Some Indian dishes that work beautifully in restaurants don't travel well to offices. Skip these for corporate catering:</p>

			<ul>
				<li>Dosas (need to be eaten immediately or they go soft)</li>
				<li>Tandoor breads beyond naan (paratha and roti can dry out)</li>
				<li>Heavily fried items that turn soggy in transit</li>
				<li>Anything with curd-based sauces that separate when reheated</li>
				<li>Spice-bombs that scare cautious eaters — keep heat moderate, offer hot sauce on the side</li>
			</ul>

			<h2>Dessert: <em>Less is More</em></h2>

			<p>For office lunches, dessert should be light. Heavy gulab jamun or kheer can push people into post-lunch food coma. Better choices:</p>

			<ul>
				<li>Mini gulab jamun (one each)</li>
				<li>Coconut barfi or kaju katli — small, sweet, photogenic</li>
				<li>Fresh fruit chaat as a lighter option</li>
				<li>Mango lassi shots in small cups</li>
			</ul>

			<h2>The <em>Goldilocks Menu</em></h2>

			<p>Here's the menu we recommend most often for corporate lunches of 50–100 guests:</p>

			<ul>
				<li>Samosas with chutneys (starter)</li>
				<li>Butter chicken (main)</li>
				<li>Paneer butter masala (vegetarian main)</li>
				<li>Dal makhani (vegan main)</li>
				<li>Basmati rice + garlic naan (sides)</li>
				<li>Mixed salad with cumin-lime dressing</li>
				<li>Mini gulab jamun (dessert)</li>
			</ul>

			<p>Covers omnivores, vegetarians, and vegans. Holds heat for two hours. Doesn't put anyone to sleep. Works for any office.</p>

			<h2>Final Thoughts</h2>

			<p>The best corporate menu isn't the most elaborate — it's the one your team will actually eat, enjoy, and walk away from feeling well-fed but still able to work. Indian food is uniquely good at this when it's planned properly.</p>

